30/07/25, 11:52โฏpm - Mohamed Aly: Complete Implementation Guide: Task Management SystemTable of ContentsProject Overview1.Backend Development with Laravel2.Frontend Development with React, Vite, and Tailwind CSS3.Database Design and Implementation4.API Development and Documentation5.Authentication and Security6.Testing Strategy7.Deployment and DevOps8.Performance Optimization9.Maintenance and Monitoring10.Project OverviewThis comprehensive implementation guide provides detailed step-by-step instructions for building a modern task management system using Laravel as the backend API framework and React with Vite and Tailwind CSS for the frontend application. The system follows atomic design principles and implements modern web development best practices to ensure scalability, maintainability, and optimal user experience.The task management system will enable users to create, organize, and track tasks efficiently while providing collaborative features for team-based work environments. The architecture separates concerns between the backend API and frontend application, allowing for independent development, testing, and deployment of each component.Backend Development with LaravelPhase 1: Environment Setup and Project InitializationThe backend development process begins with setting up a robust Laravel environment that will serve as the foundation for our task management API. Laravel provides an excellent framework for building RESTful APIs with built-in features for authentication, database management, and API resource handling.Step 1.1: Laravel Installation and ConfigurationBegin by installing Laravel using Composer, ensuring you have the latest stable version. Create a new Laravel project specifically for the task management system:ูุณุฎcomposer create-project laravel/laravel task-management-api
cd task-management-api
Configure the environment variables in the .env file to match your development environment. This includes database connection settings, application key generation, and other essential configuration parameters. The database configuration should be set up for MySQL or PostgreSQL, depending on your preference and production requirements.Generate the application key and configure the database connection:ูุณุฎphp artisan key:generate
php artisan config:cache
Step 1.2: Database Configuration and Migration SetupCreate the database schema by designing and implementing migrations for all necessary tables. The task management system requires several core entities: users, projects, tasks, comments, attachments, and notifications.Start with the users table migration, which Laravel provides by default, but customize it to include additional fields such as profile information, role assignments, and user preferences:ูุณุฎphp artisan make:migration create_users_table
php artisan make:migration create_projects_table
php artisan make:migration create_tasks_table
php artisan make:migration create_comments_table
php artisan make:migration create_attachments_table
php artisan make:migration create_notifications_table
Design the database schema with proper relationships, foreign key constraints, and indexes for optimal performance. Consider implementing soft deletes for important entities to maintain data integrity and provide recovery options.Step 1.3: Model Creation and RelationshipsCreate Eloquent models for each entity with proper relationships, accessors, mutators, and scopes. The models should implement Laravel's best practices for data handling and include proper validation rules.ูุณุฎphp artisan make:model User
php artisan make:model Project
php artisan make:model Task
php artisan make:model Comment
php artisan make:model Attachment
php artisan make:model Notification
Define relationships between models using Eloquent's relationship methods. For example, a User can have many Projects and Tasks, a Project can have many Tasks, and a Task can have many Comments and Attachments.Phase 2: API Development and Resource ManagementStep 2.1: API Resource ControllersCreate resource controllers for each entity to handle CRUD operations through RESTful API endpoints. Laravel's resource controllers provide a conventional structure for handling HTTP requests and responses.ูุณุฎphp artisan make:controller API/UserController --api
php artisan make:controller API/ProjectController --api
php artisan make:controller API/TaskController --api
php artisan make:controller API/CommentController --api
php artisan make:controller API/AttachmentController --api
Implement proper HTTP status codes, error handling, and response formatting in each controller. Use Laravel's API resources to transform model data into consistent JSON responses.Step 2.2: API Routes and Middlewareroutes/api.phpDefine API routes in the  file, organizing them logically and applying appropriate middleware for authentication, rate limiting, and CORS handling.ูุณุฎRoute::middleware('auth:sanctum')->group(function () {
    Route::apiResource('projects', ProjectController::class);
    Route::apiResource('tasks', TaskController::class);
    Route::apiResource('comments', CommentController::class);
});
Implement custom middleware for role-based access control, request validation, and API versioning to ensure proper security and maintainability.Step 2.3: Request Validation and Form RequestsCreate form request classes to handle input validation for each API endpoint. This ensures data integrity and provides consistent error responses for invalid input.ูุณุฎphp artisan make:request StoreProjectRequest
php artisan make:request UpdateProjectRequest
php artisan make:request StoreTaskRequest
php artisan make:request UpdateTaskRequest
Implement comprehensive validation rules that cover all possible input scenarios, including custom validation rules for business logic requirements.Phase 3: Authentication and AuthorizationStep 3.1: Laravel Sanctum ImplementationConfigure Laravel Sanctum for SPA authentication, which provides a lightweight authentication system perfect for single-page applications. Sanctum handles token-based authentication while maintaining session-based authentication for web routes.ูุณุฎphp artisan vendor:publish --provider="Laravel\Sanctum\SanctumServiceProvider"
php artisan migrate
Configure Sanctum middleware and CORS settings to allow requests from your frontend application domain.Step 3.2: User Registration and LoginImplement user registration and login endpoints with proper validation, password hashing, and token generation. Include email verification functionality to ensure user account security.Create authentication controllers that handle user registration, login, logout, and password reset functionality:ูุณุฎphp artisan make:controller Auth/RegisterController
php artisan make:controller Auth/LoginController
php artisan make:controller Auth/PasswordResetController
Step 3.3: Role-Based Access ControlImplement a role-based permission system that allows different user types (admin, project manager, team member) to access appropriate resources and perform authorized actions.Create roles and permissions tables with appropriate migrations and models:ูุณุฎphp artisan make:migration create_roles_table
php artisan make:migration create_permissions_table
php artisan make:migration create_role_user_table
Frontend Development with React, Vite, and Tailwind CSSPhase 1: Project Setup and ConfigurationStep 1.1: React Project Initialization with ViteCreate a new React project using Vite as the build tool, which provides faster development builds and hot module replacement compared to traditional webpack-based setups.ูุณุฎnpm create vite@latest task-management-frontend -- --template react
cd task-management-frontend
npm install
Vite offers superior performance during development with its native ES modules approach and optimized production builds. Configure Vite for optimal development experience with proper proxy settings for API calls.Step 1.2: Tailwind CSS IntegrationInstall and configure Tailwind CSS for utility-first styling that aligns with our atomic design principles. Tailwind provides excellent developer experience with its comprehensive utility classes and responsive design capabilities.ูุณุฎnpm install -D tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer
npx tailwindcss init -p
Configure Tailwind to scan your React components and create a custom configuration that matches your design system colors, fonts, and spacing defined in the atomic design specification.Step 1.3: Essential Dependencies InstallationInstall necessary dependencies for routing, state management, HTTP client, and UI components:ูุณุฎnpm install react-router-dom axios react-query @headlessui/react @heroicons/react
npm install -D @types/react @types/react-dom
These dependencies provide the foundation for building a modern React application with proper routing, data fetching, and accessible UI components.Phase 2: Component Architecture ImplementationStep 2.1: Atomic Design Structure SetupCreate a well-organized folder structure that follows atomic design principles, separating components into atoms, molecules, organisms, templates, and pages.ูุณุฎsrc/
โโโ components/
โ   โโโ atoms/
โ   โ   โโโ Button/
โ   โ   โโโ Input/
โ   โ   โโโ Avatar/
โ   โ   โโโ Icon/
โ   โโโ molecules/
โ   โ   โโโ TaskItem/
โ   โ   โโโ SearchBar/
โ   โ   โโโ UserCard/
โ   โโโ organisms/
โ   โ   โโโ TaskList/
โ   โ   โโโ ProjectBoard/
โ   โ   โโโ Navigation/

โ       โโโ DashboardLayout/

โโโ pages/

โโโ services/
โโโ utils/
โโโ styles/
This structure promotes component reusability and maintainability while making it easy for developers to locate and modify specific UI elements.Step 2.2: Atom Components DevelopmentBegin with the foundational atom components that will be used throughout the application. These include buttons, inputs, avatars, icons, and typography elements.Create a comprehensive Button component with multiple variants (primary, secondary, danger), sizes (small, medium, large), and states (loading, disabled):ูุณุฎ// components/atoms/Button/Button.jsx
import React from 'react';
import { clsx } from 'clsx';

const Button = ({ 
  variant = 'primary', 
  size = 'medium', 
  loading = false, 
  disabled = false, 
  children, 
  className,
  ...props 
}) => {
  const baseClasses = 'inline-flex items-center justify-center font-medium rounded-md transition-colors focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-offset-2';
  
  const variantClasses = {
    primary: 'bg-blue-600 text-white hover:bg-blue-700 focus:ring-blue-500',
    secondary: 'bg-white text-blue-600 border border-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-50 focus:ring-blue-500',
    danger: 'bg-red-600 text-white hover:bg-red-700 focus:ring-red-500'
  };
  
  const sizeClasses = {
    small: 'px-3 py-1.5 text-sm',
    medium: 'px-4 py-2 text-sm',
    large: 'px-6 py-3 text-base'
  };
  
  return (
    <button
      className={clsx(
        baseClasses,
        variantClasses[variant],
        sizeClasses[size],
        (disabled || loading) && 'opacity-50 cursor-not-allowed',
        className
      )}
      disabled={disabled || loading}
      {...props}
    >
      {loading && <LoadingSpinner className="mr-2" />}
      {children}
    </button>
  );
};

export default Button;
Develop similar comprehensive components for Input fields, Avatars, and other atomic elements, ensuring each component is fully accessible and follows design system specifications.Step 2.3: Molecule Components DevelopmentBuild molecule components by combining atoms to create more complex UI elements. These include form groups, task items, user cards, and navigation elements.Create a TaskItem molecule that combines multiple atoms to display task information:ูุณุฎ// components/molecules/TaskItem/TaskItem.jsx
import React from 'react';
import { Checkbox, Avatar, Badge, Button } from '../../atoms';
import { formatDate } from '../../../utils/dateUtils';

const TaskItem = ({ task, onToggleComplete, onEdit, onDelete }) => {
  return (
    <div className="flex items-center p-4 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
      <Checkbox
        checked={task.completed}
        onChange={() => onToggleComplete(task.id)}
        className="mr-3"
      />
      
      <div className="flex-1 min-w-0">
        <h3 className={`text-sm font-medium ${task.completed ? 'line-through text-gray-500' : 'text-gray-900'}`}>
          {task.title}
        </h3>
        <p className="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-1">
          Due: {formatDate(task.dueDate)}
        </p>
      </div>
      
      <div className="flex items-center space-x-2">
        <Badge variant={task.priority.toLowerCase()}>
          {task.priority}
        </Badge>
        
        <Avatar
          src={task.assignee?.avatar}
          name={task.assignee?.name}
          size="small"
        />
        
        <div className="flex space-x-1">
          <Button
            variant="ghost"
            size="small"
            onClick={() => onEdit(task)}
          >
            Edit
          </Button>
          <Button
            variant="ghost"
            size="small"
            onClick={() => onDelete(task.id)}
          >
            Delete
          </Button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default TaskItem;
Phase 3: State Management and Data FetchingStep 3.1: API Service LayerCreate a comprehensive API service layer using Axios for HTTP requests and React Query for data fetching, caching, and synchronization.ูุณุฎ// services/api.js
import axios from 'axios';

const API_BASE_URL = import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE_URL || 'http://localhost:8000/api';

const apiClient = axios.create({
  baseURL: API_BASE_URL,
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
  },
});

// Request interceptor for authentication
apiClient.interceptors.request.use((config) => {
  const token = localStorage.getItem('auth_token');
  if (token) {
    config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${token}`;
  }
  return config;
});

// Response interceptor for error handling
apiClient.interceptors.response.use(
  (response) => response,
  (error) => {
    if (error.response?.status === 401) {
      localStorage.removeItem('auth_token');
      window.location.href = '/login';
    }
    return Promise.reject(error);
  }
);

export const taskService = {
  getTasks: (params) => apiClient.get('/tasks', { params }),
  getTask: (id) => apiClient.get(`/tasks/${id}`),
  createTask: (data) => apiClient.post('/tasks', data),
  updateTask: (id, data) => apiClient.put(`/tasks/${id}`, data),
  deleteTask: (id) => apiClient.delete(`/tasks/${id}`),
};

export const projectService = {
  getProjects: () => apiClient.get('/projects'),
  getProject: (id) => apiClient.get(`/projects/${id}`),
  createProject: (data) => apiClient.post('/projects', data),
  updateProject: (id, data) => apiClient.put(`/projects/${id}`, data),
  deleteProject: (id) => apiClient.delete(`/projects/${id}`),
};

export default apiClient;
Step 3.2: React Query IntegrationImplement React Query for efficient data fetching, caching, and state management. This provides excellent developer experience with automatic background updates, optimistic updates, and error handling.ูุณุฎ// hooks/useTasks.js
import { useQuery, useMutation, useQueryClient } from 'react-query';
import { taskService } from '../services/api';

export const useTasks = (filters = {}) => {
  return useQuery(
    ['tasks', filters],
    () => taskService.getTasks(filters),
    {
      select: (data) => data.data,
      staleTime: 5 * 60 * 1000, // 5 minutes
    }
  );
};

export const useCreateTask = () => {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient();
  
  return useMutation(taskService.createTask, {
    onSuccess: () => {
      queryClient.invalidateQueries(['tasks']);
    },
  });
};

export const useUpdateTask = () => {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient();
  
  return useMutation(
    ({ id, data }) => taskService.updateTask(id, data),
    {
      onSuccess: () => {
        queryClient.invalidateQueries(['tasks']);
      },
    }
  );
};
Step 3.3: Authentication ContextCreate an authentication context to manage user state, login/logout functionality, and protected routes throughout the application.ูุณุฎ// contexts/AuthContext.jsx
import React, { createContext, useContext, useReducer, useEffect } from 'react';
import { authService } from '../services/api';

const AuthContext = createContext();

const authReducer = (state, action) => {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'LOGIN_SUCCESS':
      return {
        ...state,
        user: action.payload.user,
        token: action.payload.token,
        isAuthenticated: true,
        loading: false,
      };
    case 'LOGOUT':
      return {
        ...state,
        user: null,
        token: null,
        isAuthenticated: false,
        loading: false,
      };
    case 'SET_LOADING':
      return {
        ...state,
        loading: action.payload,
      };
    default:
      return state;
  }
};

export const AuthProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(authReducer, {
    user: null,
    token: localStorage.getItem('auth_token'),
    isAuthenticated: false,
    loading: true,
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    const initializeAuth = async () => {
      const token = localStorage.getItem('auth_token');
      if (token) {
        try {
          const response = await authService.getUser();
          dispatch({
            type: 'LOGIN_SUCCESS',
            payload: {
              user: response.data,
              token,
            },
          });
        } catch (error) {
          localStorage.removeItem('auth_token');
          dispatch({ type: 'LOGOUT' });
        }
      }
      dispatch({ type: 'SET_LOADING', payload: false });
    };

    initializeAuth();
  }, []);

  const login = async (credentials) => {
    try {
      const response = await authService.login(credentials);
      const { user, token } = response.data;
      
      localStorage.setItem('auth_token', token);
      dispatch({
        type: 'LOGIN_SUCCESS',
        payload: { user, token },
      });
      
      return { success: true };
    } catch (error) {
      return { success: false, error: error.response?.data?.message };
    }
  };

  const logout = () => {
    localStorage.removeItem('auth_token');
    dispatch({ type: 'LOGOUT' });
  };

  return (
    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ ...state, login, logout }}>
      {children}
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
};

export const useAuth = () => {
  const context = useContext(AuthContext);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error('useAuth must be used within an AuthProvider');
  }
  return context;
};
Database Design and ImplementationPhase 1: Database Schema DesignThe database schema forms the foundation of our task management system, requiring careful consideration of relationships, constraints, and performance optimization. The schema must support complex queries while maintaining data integrity and scalability.Core Entity RelationshipsThe database design centers around five primary entities: Users, Projects, Tasks, Comments, and Attachments. Each entity serves a specific purpose in the task management workflow while maintaining clear relationships with other entities.Users represent the individuals who will interact with the system, whether as administrators, project managers, or team members. The users table includes essential information such as name, email, password hash, role assignments, and profile preferences. Additionally, the table incorporates timestamps for account creation and last activity tracking, which proves valuable for user engagement analytics and security monitoring.Projects serve as containers for related tasks, providing organizational structure and collaborative workspaces. The projects table includes project name, description, status indicators, creation and completion dates, and ownership information. Projects maintain relationships with users through ownership and membership associations, allowing for flexible team assignments and access control.Tasks represent the core work items within the system, containing detailed information about individual assignments. The tasks table includes title, description, priority levels, status indicators, due dates, estimated completion times, and actual completion tracking. Tasks belong to projects and can be assigned to specific users, creating a clear hierarchy and responsibility structure.Comments enable collaborative communication around specific tasks, providing a threaded discussion system that maintains context and history. The comments table includes comment content, author information, timestamps, and parent comment references for nested discussions.Attachments support file sharing and documentation within the context of specific tasks or projects. The attachments table includes file metadata such as original filename, file size, MIME type, storage path, and upload timestamps.Advanced Schema ConsiderationsBeyond the core entities, the schema incorporates several advanced features to support comprehensive task management functionality. These include notification systems, activity logging, and permission management structures.The notifications table tracks system-generated alerts and user communications, including notification type, recipient information, read status, and related entity references. This enables real-time updates and ensures users stay informed about relevant changes and assignments.Activity logs maintain a comprehensive audit trail of all system interactions, recording user actions, entity modifications, and system events. This information proves invaluable for troubleshooting, compliance requirements, and user behavior analysis.Permission management utilizes a role-based access control system with separate tables for roles, permissions, and their associations. This flexible approach allows for granular access control while maintaining simplicity in common use cases.Phase 2: Migration ImplementationLaravel migrations provide version control for database schema changes, ensuring consistent deployment across different environments. Each migration represents a specific schema modification and can be rolled back if necessary.User Management MigrationsThe user migration extends Laravel's default user table with additional fields required for the task management system. This includes role assignments, profile information, and system preferences.ูุณุฎ// database/migrations/create_users_table.php
public function up()
{
    Schema::create('users', function (Blueprint $table) {
        $table->id();
        $table->string('name');
        $table->string('email')->unique();
        $table->timestamp('email_verified_at')->nullable();
        $table->string('password');
        $table->string('avatar')->nullable();
        $table->text('bio')->nullable();
        $table->enum('role', ['admin', 'manager', 'member'])->default('member');
        $table->json('preferences')->nullable();
        $table->timestamp('last_active_at')->nullable();
        $table->rememberToken();
        $table->timestamps();
        $table->softDeletes();
        
        $table->index(['email', 'role']);
        $table->index('last_active_at');
    });
}
Project Management MigrationsThe projects migration creates a comprehensive structure for project organization, including status tracking, team management, and progress monitoring.ูุณุฎ// database/migrations/create_projects_table.php
public function up()
{
    Schema::create('projects', function (Blueprint $table) {
        $table->id();
        $table->string('name');
        $table->text('description')->nullable();
        $table->enum('status', ['planning', 'active', 'on_hold', 'completed', 'cancelled'])->default('planning');
        $table->enum('priority', ['low', 'medium', 'high', 'critical'])->default('medium');
        $table->date('start_date')->nullable();
        $table->date('due_date')->nullable();
        $table->date('completed_date')->nullable();
        $table->decimal('budget', 10, 2)->nullable();
        $table->foreignId('owner_id')->constrained('users')->onDelete('cascade');
        $table->json('settings')->nullable();
        $table->timestamps();
        $table->softDeletes();
        
        $table->index(['status', 'priority']);
        $table->index(['owner_id', 'status']);
        $table->index(['due_date', 'status']);
    });
}
Task Management MigrationsThe tasks migration implements a comprehensive task tracking system with support for complex workflows, dependencies, and progress monitoring.ูุณุฎ// database/migrations/create_tasks_table.php
public function up()
{
    Schema::create('tasks', function (Blueprint $table) {
        $table->id();
        $table->string('title');
        $table->text('description')->nullable();
        $table->enum('status', ['todo', 'in_progress', 'review', 'done', 'cancelled'])->default('todo');
        $table->enum('priority', ['low', 'medium', 'high', 'critical'])->default('medium');
        $table->foreignId('project_id')->constrained()->onDelete('cascade');
        $table->foreignId('assignee_id')->nullable()->constrained('users')->onDelete('set null');
        $table->foreignId('creator_id')->constrained('users')->onDelete('cascade');
        $table->datetime('due_date')->nullable();
        $table->datetime('started_at')->nullable();
        $table->datetime('completed_at')->nullable();
        $table->integer('estimated_hours')->nullable();
        $table->integer('actual_hours')->nullable();
        $table->json('tags')->nullable();
        $table->json('custom_fields')->nullable();
        $table->timestamps();
        $table->softDeletes();
        
        $table->index(['project_id', 'status']);
        $table->index(['assignee_id', 'status']);
        $table->index(['due_date', 'status']);
        $table->index(['priority', 'status']);
        $table->fullText(['title', 'description']);
    });
}
API Development and DocumentationPhase 1: RESTful API Design PrinciplesThe API design follows RESTful principles to ensure consistency, predictability, and ease of use for frontend developers and potential third-party integrations. Each endpoint serves a specific purpose while maintaining standard HTTP methods and status codes.Resource-Based URL StructureAPI endpoints follow a logical resource-based structure that reflects the application's data model. This approach makes the API intuitive and self-documenting, reducing the learning curve for developers.The base URL structure follows the pattern /api/v1/{resource} with appropriate HTTP methods for different operations. For example, task management endpoints include:GET /api/v1/tasksโข - Retrieve all tasks with optional filtering - Create a new taskPOST /api/v1/tasksโขGET /api/v1/tasks/{id}โข - Retrieve a specific taskPUT /api/v1/tasks/{id}โข - Update a specific taskDELETE /api/v1/tasks/{id}โข - Delete a specific taskNested resources maintain the hierarchical relationship between entities, such as /api/v1/projects/{id}/tasks for retrieving tasks within a specific project.Request and Response FormattingAll API requests and responses use JSON format with consistent structure and naming conventions. Request bodies include only necessary data with proper validation, while responses provide comprehensive information including metadata and pagination details.Response format follows a standardized structure:ูุณุฎ{
  "data": {
    // Resource data or array of resources
  },
  "meta": {
    "pagination": {
      "current_page": 1,
      "per_page": 15,
      "total": 150,
      "last_page": 10
    }
  },
  "links": {
    "first": "http://api.example.com/tasks?page=1",
    "last": "http://api.example.com/tasks?page=10",
    "prev": null,
    "next": "http://api.example.com/tasks?page=2"
  }
}
Error responses maintain consistency with appropriate HTTP status codes and detailed error information:ูุณุฎ{
  "error": {
    "message": "Validation failed",
    "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
    "details": {
      "title": ["The title field is required."],
      "due_date": ["The due date must be a valid date."]
    }
  }
}
Phase 2: Controller ImplementationLaravel controllers handle HTTP requests and coordinate between the request layer and business logic. Each controller focuses on a specific resource while maintaining separation of concerns and following single responsibility principles.Task Controller ImplementationThe TaskController manages all task-related operations with comprehensive error handling, validation, and response formatting.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers\API;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use App\Http\Requests\StoreTaskRequest;
use App\Http\Requests\UpdateTaskRequest;
use App\Http\Resources\TaskResource;
use App\Models\Task;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use Illuminate\Http\Response;

class TaskController extends Controller
{
    public function index(Request $request)
    {
        $query = Task::with(['project', 'assignee', 'creator'])
            ->when($request->project_id, function ($query, $projectId) {
                return $query->where('project_id', $projectId);
            })
            ->when($request->assignee_id, function ($query, $assigneeId) {
                return $query->where('assignee_id', $assigneeId);
            })
            ->when($request->status, function ($query, $status) {
                return $query->where('status', $status);
            })
            ->when($request->priority, function ($query, $priority) {
                return $query->where('priority', $priority);
            })
            ->when($request->search, function ($query, $search) {
                return $query->where(function ($q) use ($search) {
                    $q->where('title', 'like', "%{$search}%")
                      ->orWhere('description', 'like', "%{$search}%");
                });
            })
            ->when($request->due_date_from, function ($query, $date) {
                return $query->where('due_date', '>=', $date);
            })
            ->when($request->due_date_to, function ($query, $date) {
                return $query->where('due_date', '<=', $date);
            })
            ->orderBy($request->sort_by ?? 'created_at', $request->sort_direction ?? 'desc');

        $tasks = $query->paginate($request->per_page ?? 15);

        return TaskResource::collection($tasks);
    }

    public function store(StoreTaskRequest $request)
    {
        $task = Task::create([
            ...$request->validated(),
            'creator_id' => auth()->id(),
        ]);

        $task->load(['project', 'assignee', 'creator']);

        return new TaskResource($task);
    }

    public function show(Task $task)
    {
        $task->load(['project', 'assignee', 'creator', 'comments.author', 'attachments']);
        
        return new TaskResource($task);
    }

    public function update(UpdateTaskRequest $request, Task $task)
    {
        $this->authorize('update', $task);

        $task->update($request->validated());
        $task->load(['project', 'assignee', 'creator']);

        return new TaskResource($task);
    }

    public function destroy(Task $task)
    {
        $this->authorize('delete', $task);

        $task->delete();

        return response()->noContent();
    }

    public function bulkUpdate(Request $request)
    {
        $request->validate([
            'task_ids' => 'required|array',
            'task_ids.*' => 'exists:tasks,id',
            'updates' => 'required|array',
        ]);

        $tasks = Task::whereIn('id', $request->task_ids)->get();

        foreach ($tasks as $task) {
            $this->authorize('update', $task);
            $task->update($request->updates);
        }

        return response()->json(['message' => 'Tasks updated successfully']);
    }
}
Project Controller ImplementationThe ProjectController manages project lifecycle operations with team management capabilities and comprehensive project analytics.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers\API;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use App\Http\Requests\StoreProjectRequest;
use App\Http\Requests\UpdateProjectRequest;
use App\Http\Resources\ProjectResource;
use App\Models\Project;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;

class ProjectController extends Controller
{
    public function index(Request $request)
    {
        $query = Project::with(['owner', 'members', 'tasks'])
            ->withCount(['tasks', 'completedTasks'])
            ->when($request->status, function ($query, $status) {
                return $query->where('status', $status);
            })
            ->when($request->owner_id, function ($query, $ownerId) {
                return $query->where('owner_id', $ownerId);
            })
            ->when($request->search, function ($query, $search) {
                return $query->where(function ($q) use ($search) {
                    $q->where('name', 'like', "%{$search}%")
                      ->orWhere('description', 'like', "%{$search}%");
                });
            });

        $projects = $query->paginate($request->per_page ?? 15);

        return ProjectResource::collection($projects);
    }

    public function store(StoreProjectRequest $request)
    {
        $project = Project::create([
            ...$request->validated(),
            'owner_id' => auth()->id(),
        ]);

        $project->load(['owner', 'members']);

        return new ProjectResource($project);
    }

    public function show(Project $project)
    {
        $project->load([
            'owner',
            'members',
            'tasks.assignee',
            'tasks.creator',
            'recentActivity'
        ]);

        return new ProjectResource($project);
    }

    public function update(UpdateProjectRequest $request, Project $project)
    {
        $this->authorize('update', $project);

        $project->update($request->validated());
        $project->load(['owner', 'members']);

        return new ProjectResource($project);
    }

    public function destroy(Project $project)
    {
        $this->authorize('delete', $project);

        $project->delete();

        return response()->noContent();
    }

    public function addMember(Request $request, Project $project)
    {
        $request->validate([
            'user_id' => 'required|exists:users,id',
            'role' => 'required|in:member,manager',
        ]);

        $this->authorize('manage-members', $project);

        $project->members()->attach($request->user_id, [
            'role' => $request->role,
            'joined_at' => now(),
        ]);

        return response()->json(['message' => 'Member added successfully']);
    }

    public function removeMember(Request $request, Project $project)
    {
        $request->validate([
            'user_id' => 'required|exists:users,id',
        ]);

        $this->authorize('manage-members', $project);

        $project->members()->detach($request->user_id);

        return response()->json(['message' => 'Member removed successfully']);
    }

    public function analytics(Project $project)
    {
        $this->authorize('view', $project);

        $analytics = [
            'task_statistics' => [
                'total' => $project->tasks()->count(),
                'completed' => $project->tasks()->where('status', 'done')->count(),
                'in_progress' => $project->tasks()->where('status', 'in_progress')->count(),
                'overdue' => $project->tasks()->where('due_date', '<', now())->where('status', '!=', 'done')->count(),
            ],
            'team_performance' => $project->members()
                ->withCount(['assignedTasks', 'completedTasks'])
                ->get()
                ->map(function ($member) {
                    return [
                        'user' => $member->only(['id', 'name', 'email']),
                        'assigned_tasks' => $member->assigned_tasks_count,
                        'completed_tasks' => $member->completed_tasks_count,
                        'completion_rate' => $member->assigned_tasks_count > 0 
                            ? round(($member->completed_tasks_count / $member->assigned_tasks_count) * 100, 2)
                            : 0,
                    ];
                }),
            'timeline' => $project->tasks()
                ->selectRaw('DATE(created_at) as date, COUNT(*) as tasks_created')
                ->where('created_at', '>=', now()->subDays(30))
                ->groupBy('date')
                ->orderBy('date')
                ->get(),
            'priority_distribution' => $project->tasks()
                ->selectRaw('priority, COUNT(*) as count')
                ->groupBy('priority')
                ->get()
                ->pluck('count', 'priority'),
        ];

        return response()->json($analytics);
    }
}
Phase 3: API Resource TransformationLaravel API resources provide a transformation layer between Eloquent models and JSON responses, ensuring consistent data formatting and selective field exposure.Task Resource ImplementationThe TaskResource transforms task model data into a consistent API response format with conditional field inclusion based on context and user permissions.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace App\Http\Resources;

use Illuminate\Http\Resources\Json\JsonResource;

class TaskResource extends JsonResource
{
    public function toArray($request)
    {
        return [
            'id' => $this->id,
            'title' => $this->title,
            'description' => $this->description,
            'status' => $this->status,
            'priority' => $this->priority,
            'due_date' => $this->due_date?->toISOString(),
            'started_at' => $this->started_at?->toISOString(),
            'completed_at' => $this->completed_at?->toISOString(),
            'estimated_hours' => $this->estimated_hours,
            'actual_hours' => $this->actual_hours,
            'tags' => $this->tags ?? [],
            'custom_fields' => $this->custom_fields ?? [],
            'created_at' => $this->created_at->toISOString(),
            'updated_at' => $this->updated_at->toISOString(),
            
            // Relationships
            'project' => new ProjectResource($this->whenLoaded('project')),
            'assignee' => new UserResource($this->whenLoaded('assignee')),
            'creator' => new UserResource($this->whenLoaded('creator')),
            'comments' => CommentResource::collection($this->whenLoaded('comments')),
            'attachments' => AttachmentResource::collection($this->whenLoaded('attachments')),
            
            // Computed fields
            'is_overdue' => $this->due_date && $this->due_date->isPast() && $this->status !== 'done',
            'days_until_due' => $this->due_date ? now()->diffInDays($this->due_date, false) : null,
            'completion_percentage' => $this->calculateCompletionPercentage(),
            'can_edit' => $this->when(auth()->check(), function () {
                return auth()->user()->can('update', $this->resource);
            }),
            'can_delete' => $this->when(auth()->check(), function () {
                return auth()->user()->can('delete', $this->resource);
            }),
        ];
    }

    public function with($request)
    {
        return [
            'meta' => [
                'status_options' => [
                    'todo' => 'To Do',
                    'in_progress' => 'In Progress',
                    'review' => 'Review',
                    'done' => 'Done',
                    'cancelled' => 'Cancelled',
                ],
                'priority_options' => [
                    'low' => 'Low',
                    'medium' => 'Medium',
                    'high' => 'High',
                    'critical' => 'Critical',
                ],
            ],
        ];
    }
}
Authentication and SecurityPhase 1: Laravel Sanctum ConfigurationLaravel Sanctum provides a lightweight authentication system perfect for SPAs and mobile applications. The configuration process involves several steps to ensure secure token-based authentication while maintaining session compatibility for web routes.Sanctum Installation and SetupBegin by installing Laravel Sanctum through Composer and publishing the necessary configuration files and migrations.ูุณุฎcomposer require laravel/sanctum
php artisan vendor:publish --provider="Laravel\Sanctum\SanctumServiceProvider"
php artisan migrate
Configure Sanctum middleware in the app/Http/Kernel.php file to enable API token authentication:ูุณุฎ'api' => [
    \Laravel\Sanctum\Http\Middleware\EnsureFrontendRequestsAreStateful::class,
    'throttle:api',
    \Illuminate\Routing\Middleware\SubstituteBindings::class,
],
config/sanctum.phpUpdate the  configuration file to specify allowed domains for SPA authentication and token expiration settings:ูุณุฎ'stateful' => explode(',', env('SANCTUM_STATEFUL_DOMAINS', sprintf(
    '%s%s',
    'localhost,localhost:3000,127.0.0.1,127.0.0.1:8000,::1',
    env('APP_URL') ? ','.parse_url(env('APP_URL'), PHP_URL_HOST) : ''
))),

'expiration' => env('SANCTUM_TOKEN_EXPIRATION', 60 * 24 * 7), // 7 days
CORS ConfigurationConfigure Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) settings to allow requests from your frontend application domain. Update the  file:config/cors.phpูุณุฎ'paths' => ['api/*', 'sanctum/csrf-cookie'],
'allowed_methods' => ['*'],
'allowed_origins' => [
    env('FRONTEND_URL', 'http://localhost:3000'),
    env('APP_URL', 'http://localhost:8000'),
],
'allowed_origins_patterns' => [],
'allowed_headers' => ['*'],
'exposed_headers' => [],
'max_age' => 0,
'supports_credentials' => true,
Phase 2: Authentication ControllersImplement comprehensive authentication controllers that handle user registration, login, logout, password reset, and email verification functionality.Registration ControllerThe registration controller manages new user account creation with proper validation, email verification, and welcome notifications.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers\Auth;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use App\Http\Requests\RegisterRequest;
use App\Models\User;
use Illuminate\Auth\Events\Registered;
use Illuminate\Http\Response;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Hash;

class RegisterController extends Controller
{
    public function register(RegisterRequest $request)
    {
        $user = User::create([
            'name' => $request->name,
            'email' => $request->email,
            'password' => Hash::make($request->password),
            'role' => 'member',
        ]);

        event(new Registered($user));

        $token = $user->createToken('auth-token')->plainTextToken;

        return response()->json([
            'user' => $user,
            'token' => $token,
            'message' => 'Registration successful. Please verify your email address.',
        ], Response::HTTP_CREATED);
    }

    public function verifyEmail(Request $request)
    {
        $request->validate([
            'id' => 'required|integer',
            'hash' => 'required|string',
        ]);

        $user = User::findOrFail($request->id);

        if (!hash_equals((string) $request->hash, sha1($user->getEmailForVerification()))) {
            return response()->json([
                'message' => 'Invalid verification link.',
            ], Response::HTTP_FORBIDDEN);
        }

        if ($user->hasVerifiedEmail()) {
            return response()->json([
                'message' => 'Email already verified.',
            ]);
        }

        $user->markEmailAsVerified();

        return response()->json([
            'message' => 'Email verified successfully.',
        ]);
    }

    public function resendVerification(Request $request)
    {
        $request->validate(['email' => 'required|email']);

        $user = User::where('email', $request->email)->first();

        if (!$user) {
            return response()->json([
                'message' => 'User not found.',
            ], Response::HTTP_NOT_FOUND);
        }

        if ($user->hasVerifiedEmail()) {
            return response()->json([
                'message' => 'Email already verified.',
            ]);
        }

        $user->sendEmailVerificationNotification();

        return response()->json([
            'message' => 'Verification email sent.',
        ]);
    }
}
Login ControllerThe login controller handles user authentication with rate limiting, failed attempt tracking, and secure token generation.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers\Auth;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use App\Http\Requests\LoginRequest;
use App\Models\User;
use Illuminate\Http\Response;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Hash;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\RateLimiter;
use Illuminate\Validation\ValidationException;

class LoginController extends Controller
{
    public function login(LoginRequest $request)
    {
        $this->ensureIsNotRateLimited($request);

        $user = User::where('email', $request->email)->first();

        if (!$user || !Hash::check($request->password, $user->password)) {
            RateLimiter::hit($this->throttleKey($request));

            throw ValidationException::withMessages([
                'email' => ['The provided credentials are incorrect.'],
            ]);
        }

        if (!$user->hasVerifiedEmail()) {
            throw ValidationException::withMessages([
                'email' => ['Please verify your email address before logging in.'],
            ]);
        }

        RateLimiter::clear($this->throttleKey($request));

        $token = $user->createToken('auth-token', ['*'], now()->addDays(7))->plainTextToken;

        $user->update(['last_active_at' => now()]);

        return response()->json([
            'user' => $user,
            'token' => $token,
            'message' => 'Login successful.',
        ]);
    }

    public function logout(Request $request)
    {
        $request->user()->currentAccessToken()->delete();

        return response()->json([
            'message' => 'Logged out successfully.',
        ]);
    }

    public function logoutAll(Request $request)
    {
        $request->user()->tokens()->delete();

        return response()->json([
            'message' => 'Logged out from all devices successfully.',
        ]);
    }

    protected function ensureIsNotRateLimited(Request $request)
    {
        if (RateLimiter::tooManyAttempts($this->throttleKey($request), 5)) {
            $seconds = RateLimiter::availableIn($this->throttleKey($request));

            throw ValidationException::withMessages([
                'email' => ["Too many login attempts. Please try again in {$seconds} seconds."],
            ]);
        }
    }

    protected function throttleKey(Request $request)
    {
        return strtolower($request->input('email')) . '|' . $request->ip();
    }
}
Phase 3: Authorization and PermissionsImplement a comprehensive authorization system using Laravel policies and gates to control access to resources based on user roles and ownership.Task Policy ImplementationThe TaskPolicy defines authorization rules for task-related operations, considering user roles, project membership, and task ownership.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace App\Policies;

use App\Models\Task;
use App\Models\User;
use Illuminate\Auth\Access\HandlesAuthorization;

class TaskPolicy
{
    use HandlesAuthorization;

    public function viewAny(User $user)
    {
        return true; // Users can view tasks they have access to
    }

    public function view(User $user, Task $task)
    {
        return $user->id === $task->creator_id
            || $user->id === $task->assignee_id
            || $user->id === $task->project->owner_id
            || $task->project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->exists()
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function create(User $user)
    {
        return $user->role !== 'guest';
    }

    public function update(User $user, Task $task)
    {
        return $user->id === $task->creator_id
            || $user->id === $task->assignee_id
            || $user->id === $task->project->owner_id
            || ($task->project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->wherePivot('role', 'manager')->exists())
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function delete(User $user, Task $task)
    {
        return $user->id === $task->creator_id
            || $user->id === $task->project->owner_id
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function assign(User $user, Task $task)
    {
        return $user->id === $task->project->owner_id
            || ($task->project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->wherePivot('role', 'manager')->exists())
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function changeStatus(User $user, Task $task)
    {
        return $user->id === $task->assignee_id
            || $user->id === $task->creator_id
            || $user->id === $task->project->owner_id
            || ($task->project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->wherePivot('role', 'manager')->exists())
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }
}
Project Policy ImplementationThe ProjectPolicy manages access control for project-related operations, including team management and project administration.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace App\Policies;

use App\Models\Project;
use App\Models\User;
use Illuminate\Auth\Access\HandlesAuthorization;

class ProjectPolicy
{
    use HandlesAuthorization;

    public function viewAny(User $user)
    {
        return true;
    }

    public function view(User $user, Project $project)
    {
        return $user->id === $project->owner_id
            || $project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->exists()
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function create(User $user)
    {
        return $user->role !== 'guest';
    }

    public function update(User $user, Project $project)
    {
        return $user->id === $project->owner_id
            || ($project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->wherePivot('role', 'manager')->exists())
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function delete(User $user, Project $project)
    {
        return $user->id === $project->owner_id
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function manageMembers(User $user, Project $project)
    {
        return $user->id === $project->owner_id
            || ($project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->wherePivot('role', 'manager')->exists())
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }

    public function viewAnalytics(User $user, Project $project)
    {
        return $user->id === $project->owner_id
            || ($project->members()->where('user_id', $user->id)->wherePivot('role', 'manager')->exists())
            || $user->role === 'admin';
    }
}
Testing StrategyPhase 1: Backend Testing with PHPUnitComprehensive testing ensures code reliability, prevents regressions, and facilitates confident refactoring. The testing strategy encompasses unit tests, integration tests, and feature tests covering all critical application functionality.Unit Testing for Models and ServicesUnit tests focus on individual components in isolation, testing business logic, model relationships, and service methods without external dependencies.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace Tests\Unit;

use App\Models\Task;
use App\Models\User;
use App\Models\Project;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Testing\RefreshDatabase;
use Tests\TestCase;

class TaskTest extends TestCase
{
    use RefreshDatabase;

    public function test_task_belongs_to_project()
    {
        $project = Project::factory()->create();
        $task = Task::factory()->create(['project_id' => $project->id]);

        $this->assertInstanceOf(Project::class, $task->project);
        $this->assertEquals($project->id, $task->project->id);
    }

    public function test_task_can_be_assigned_to_user()
    {
        $user = User::factory()->create();
        $task = Task::factory()->create(['assignee_id' => $user->id]);

        $this->assertInstanceOf(User::class, $task->assignee);
        $this->assertEquals($user->id, $task->assignee->id);
    }

    public function test_task_calculates_overdue_status_correctly()
    {
        $overdueTask = Task::factory()->create([
            'due_date' => now()->subDays(1),
            'status' => 'in_progress'
        ]);

        $onTimeTask = Task::factory()->create([
            'due_date' => now()->addDays(1),
            'status' => 'in_progress'
        ]);

        $completedTask = Task::factory()->create([
            'due_date' => now()->subDays(1),
            'status' => 'done'
        ]);

        $this->assertTrue($overdueTask->isOverdue());
        $this->assertFalse($onTimeTask->isOverdue());
        $this->assertFalse($completedTask->isOverdue());
    }

    public function test_task_completion_updates_timestamps()
    {
        $task = Task::factory()->create(['status' => 'in_progress']);

        $task->markAsCompleted();

        $this->assertEquals('done', $task->status);
        $this->assertNotNull($task->completed_at);
    }

    public function test_task_priority_scopes_work_correctly()
    {
        Task::factory()->create(['priority' => 'high']);
        Task::factory()->create(['priority' => 'medium']);
        Task::factory()->create(['priority' => 'low']);

        $highPriorityTasks = Task::highPriority()->get();
        $criticalTasks = Task::critical()->get();

        $this->assertCount(1, $highPriorityTasks);
        $this->assertCount(0, $criticalTasks);
    }
}
Feature Testing for API EndpointsFeature tests verify complete user workflows and API endpoint functionality, including authentication, authorization, and data persistence.ูุณุฎ<?php

namespace Tests\Feature;

use App\Models\User;
use App\Models\Project;
use App\Models\Task;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Testing\RefreshDatabase;
use Laravel\Sanctum\Sanctum;
use Tests\TestCase;

class TaskApiTest extends TestCase
{
    use RefreshDatabase;

    protected function setUp(): void
    {
        parent::setUp();
        $this->seed();
    }

    public function test_authenticated_user_can_create_task()
    {
        $user = User::factory()->create();
        $project = Project::factory()->create(['owner_id' => $user->id]);

        Sanctum::actingAs($user);

        $taskData = [
            'title' => 'Test Task',
            'description' => 'Test task description',
            'project_id' => $project->id,
            'priority' => 'high',
            'due_date' => now()->addDays(7)->toISOString(),
        ];

        $response = $this->postJson('/api/tasks', $taskData);

        $response->assertStatus(201)
                ->assertJsonStructure([
                    'data' => [
                        'id',
                        'title',
                        'description',
                        'status',
                        'priority',
                        'due_date',
                        'project',
                        'creator',
                    ]
                ]);

        $this->assertDatabaseHas('tasks', [
            'title' => 'Test Task',
            'project_id' => $project->id,
            'creator_id' => $user->id,
        ]);
    }

    public function test_user_cannot_create_task_in_unauthorized_project()
    {
        $user = User::factory()->create();
        $otherUser = User::factory()->create();
        $project = Project::factory()->create(['owner_id' => $otherUser->id]);

        Sanctum::actingAs($user);

        $taskData = [
            'title' => 'Unauthorized Task',
            'project_id' => $project->id,
        ];

        $response = $this->postJson('/api/tasks', $taskData);

        $response->assertStatus(403);
    }

    public function test_user_can_update_own_task()
    {
        $user = User::factory()->create();
        $project = Project::factory()->create(['owner_id' => $user->id]);
        $task = Task::factory()->create([
            'project_id' => $project->id,
            'creator_id' => $user->id,
        ]);

        Sanctum::actingAs($user);

        $updateData = [
            'title' => 'Updated Task Title',
            'status' => 'in_progress',
        ];

        $response = $this->putJson("/api/tasks/{$task->id}", $updateData);

        $response->assertStatus(200)
                ->assertJson([
                    'data' => [
                        'title' => 'Updated Task Title',
                        'status' => 'in_progress',
                    ]
                ]);

        $this->assertDatabaseHas('tasks', [
            'id' => $task->id,
            'title' => 'Updated Task Title',
            'status' => 'in_progress',
        ]);
    }

    public function test_task_filtering_works_correctly()
    {
        $user = User::factory()->create();
        $project = Project::factory()->create(['owner_id' => $user->id]);
        
        Task::factory()->create([
            'project_id' => $project->id,
            'status' => 'todo',
            'priority' => 'high',
        ]);
        
        Task::factory()->create([
            'project_id' => $project->id,
            'status' => 'done',
            'priority' => 'low',
        ]);

        Sanctum::actingAs($user);

        // Test status filtering
        $response = $this->getJson('/api/tasks?status=todo');
        $response->assertStatus(200);
        $tasks = $response->json('data');
        $this->assertCount(1, $tasks);
        $this->assertEquals('todo', $tasks[0]['status']);

        // Test priority filtering
        $response = $this->getJson('/api/tasks?priority=high');
        $response->assertStatus(200);
        $tasks = $response->json('data');
        $this->assertCount(1, $tasks);
        $this->assertEquals('high', $tasks[0]['priority']);
    }

    public function test_task_search_functionality()
    {
        $user = User::factory()->create();
        $project = Project::factory()->create(['owner_id' => $user->id]);
        
        Task::factory()->create([
            'project_id' => $project->id,
            'title' => 'Important Meeting Preparation',
            'description' => 'Prepare slides for client presentation',
        ]);
        
        Task::factory()->create([
            'project_id' => $project->id,
            'title' => 'Code Review',
            'description' => 'Review pull request for new feature',
        ]);

        Sanctum::actingAs($user);

        $response = $this->getJson('/api/tasks?search=meeting');
        $response->assertStatus(200);
        $tasks = $response->json('data');
        $this->assertCount(1, $tasks);
        $this->assertStringContainsString('Meeting', $tasks[0]['title']);

        $response = $this->getJson('/api/tasks?search=review');
        $response->assertStatus(200);
        $tasks = $response->json('data');
        $this->assertCount(1, $tasks);
        $this->assertStringContainsString('Review', $tasks[0]['title']);
    }
}
Phase 2: Frontend Testing with Jest and React Testing LibraryFrontend testing ensures component functionality, user interactions, and integration with backend APIs work correctly across different scenarios and user flows.Component Unit TestingComponent unit tests verify individual React components render correctly and handle user interactions appropriately.ูุณุฎ// src/components/atoms/Button/Button.test.jsx
import React from 'react';
import { render, screen, fireEvent } from '@testing-library/react';
import '@testing-library/jest-dom';
import Button from './Button';

describe('Button Component', () => {
  test('renders button with correct text', () => {
    render(<Button>Click me</Button>);
    expect(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /click me/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  test('applies primary variant styles by default', () => {
    render(<Button>Primary Button</Button>);
    const button = screen.getByRole('button');
    expect(button).toHaveClass('bg-blue-600', 'text-white');
  });

  test('applies secondary variant styles when specified', () => {
    render(<Button variant="secondary">Secondary Button</Button>);
    const button = screen.getByRole('button');
    expect(button).toHaveClass('bg-white', 'text-blue-600', 'border-blue-600');
  });

  test('shows loading state correctly', () => {
    render(<Button loading>Loading Button</Button>);
    const button = screen.getByRole('button');
    expect(button).toBeDisabled();
    expect(button).toHaveClass('opacity-50', 'cursor-not-allowed');
  });

  test('handles click events', () => {
    const handleClick = jest.fn();
    render(<Button onClick={handleClick}>Clickable Button</Button>);
    
    fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button'));
    expect(handleClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
  });

  test('does not trigger click when disabled', () => {
    const handleClick = jest.fn();
    render(<Button onClick={handleClick} disabled>Disabled Button</Button>);
    
    fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button'));
    expect(handleClick).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
  });
});

import React from 'react';
import { render, screen, fireEvent, waitFor } from '@testing-library/react';
import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from 'react-query';
import { BrowserRouter } from 'react-router-dom';
import '@testing-library/jest-dom';
import TaskList from './TaskList';
import { AuthProvider } from '../../../contexts/AuthContext';

// Mock API calls
jest.mock('../../../services/api', () => ({
  taskService: {
    getTasks: jest.fn(),
    updateTask: jest.fn(),
    deleteTask: jest.fn(),
  },
}));

const mockTasks = [
  {
    id: 1,
    title: 'Complete project documentation',
    description: 'Write comprehensive documentation for the new feature',
    status: 'todo',
    priority: 'high',
    due_date: '2024-02-15T10:00:00Z',
    assignee: {
      id: 1,
      name: 'John Doe',
      avatar: 'https://example.com/avatar.jpg',
    },
    project: {
      id: 1,
      name: 'Website Redesign',
    },
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    title: 'Review pull requests',
    description: 'Review and merge pending pull requests',
    status: 'in_progress',
    priority: 'medium',
    due_date: '2024-02-10T15:30:00Z',
    assignee: {
      id: 2,
      name: 'Jane Smith',
      avatar: 'https://example.com/avatar2.jpg',
    },
    project: {
      id: 1,
      name: 'Website Redesign',
    },
  },
];

const TestWrapper = ({ children }) => {
  const queryClient = new QueryClient({
    defaultOptions: {
      queries: { retry: false },
      mutations: { retry: false },
    },
  });

  return (
    <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
      <BrowserRouter>
        <AuthProvider>
          {children}
        </AuthProvider>
      </BrowserRouter>
    </QueryClientProvider>
  );
};

describe('TaskList Component', () => {
  beforeEach(() => {
    jest.clearAllMocks();
  });

  test('renders task list with correct data', async () => {
    const { taskService } = require('../../../services/api');
    taskService.getTasks.mockResolvedValue({ data: mockTasks });

    render(
      <TestWrapper>
        <TaskList />
      </TestWrapper>
    );

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(screen.getByText('Complete project documentation')).toBeInTheDocument();
      expect(screen.getByText('Review pull requests')).toBeInTheDocument();
    });
  });

  test('filters tasks by status', async () => {
    const { taskService } = require('../../../services/api');
    taskService.getTasks.mockResolvedValue({ data: mockTasks });

    render(
      <TestWrapper>
        <TaskList />
      </TestWrapper>
    );

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(screen.getByText('Complete project documentation')).toBeInTheDocument();
    });

    // Filter by 'In Progress' status
    const statusFilter = screen.getByLabelText(/status/i);
    fireEvent.change(statusFilter, { target: { value: 'in_progress' } });

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(taskService.getTasks).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
        expect.objectContaining({ status: 'in_progress' })
      );
    });
  });

  test('handles task completion toggle', async () => {
    const { taskService } = require('../../../services/api');
    taskService.getTasks.mockResolvedValue({ data: mockTasks });
    taskService.updateTask.mockResolvedValue({ data: { ...mockTasks[0], status: 'done' } });

    render(
      <TestWrapper>
        <TaskList />
      </TestWrapper>
    );

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(screen.getByText('Complete project documentation')).toBeInTheDocument();
    });

    const checkbox = screen.getAllByRole('checkbox')[0];
    fireEvent.click(checkbox);

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(taskService.updateTask).toHaveBeenCalledWith(1, { status: 'done' });
    });
  });

  test('handles task deletion', async () => {
    const { taskService } = require('../../../services/api');
    taskService.getTasks.mockResolvedValue({ data: mockTasks });
    taskService.deleteTask.mockResolvedValue({});

    render(
      <TestWrapper>
        <TaskList />
      </TestWrapper>
    );

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(screen.getByText('Complete project documentation')).toBeInTheDocument();
    });

    const deleteButton = screen.getAllByText(/delete/i)[0];
    fireEvent.click(deleteButton);

    // Confirm deletion in modal

31/12/25, 2:16โฏam - Jimmy: ูุง ูู ููุฏ ุจุณูุท ุจุงุณุชุฎุฏุงู Python ู pytube ู facebook-downloader:

```
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import os

def download_video(url):
    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
    video_url = soup.find('video').get('src')
    video_response = requests.get(video_url)
    with open('video.mp4', 'wb') as f:
        f.write(video_response.content)

url = input("Enter Facebook video URL: ")
download_video(url)
```

ููู ูุฌุจ ููุงุญุธุฉ ุฃู ูุฐุง ุงูููุฏ ูุฏ ูุง ูุนูู ุจุณุจุจ ุณูุงุณุงุช ููุณุจูู ุงููุชุบูุฑุฉ ูุฃูุถูุง ูุฏ ูุชุทูุจ ุชุณุฌูู ุงูุฏุฎูู ุฃู ุงุณุชุฎุฏุงู API ุงูุฑุณูู ูููุณุจูู.

ุจุฏูู ุขุฎุฑ ูู ุงุณุชุฎุฏุงู ููุชุจุฉ `facebook-downloader` ูุจุงุดุฑุฉู:

```

```

ุชุฃูุฏ ูู ุชุซุจูุช ุงูููุชุจุงุช ุงููุทููุจุฉ ุจุงุณุชุฎุฏุงู pip:

31/12/25, 2:17โฏam - Mohamed Aly: @โจMeta AIโฉ ุญููู ู Ruby
31/12/25, 2:17โฏam - Jimmy: ูุง ูู ุงูููุฏ ุงูููุญููู ุฅูู Ruby:

```
require 'httparty'
require 'nokogiri'
require 'fileutils'

def download_video(url)
  response = HTTParty.get(url)
  doc = Nokogiri::HTML(response.body)
  video_url = doc.at('video')['src']
  video_response = HTTParty.get(video_url)
  File.open('video.mp4', 'wb') do |f|
    f.write(video_response.body)
  end
end

puts "Enter Facebook video URL: "
url = gets.chomp
download_video(url)
```

ุจุฏูู ุขุฎุฑ ูู ุงุณุชุฎุฏุงู ููุชุจุฉ `facebook-downloader` ูุจุงุดุฑุฉูุ ููููุง ุบูุฑ ูุชููุฑุฉ ุจุดูู ูุจุงุดุฑ ูู Rubyุ ููููู ุงุณุชุฎุฏุงู `facebook_api` ุฃู `koala` ููุชุนุงูู ูุน API ููุณุจูู.

ุชุฃูุฏ ูู ุชุซุจูุช ุงูููุชุจุงุช ุงููุทููุจุฉ ุจุงุณุชุฎุฏุงู gem:
```
bash
```
